# Testing Rules

## Philosophy
- Tests verify BEHAVIOR, not implementation details
- Each test tests ONE thing — name it clearly
- Test the happy path first, then edge cases, then error cases

## Backend (pytest)
- Location: `backend/tests/`
- Use `httpx.AsyncClient` to test API endpoints end-to-end
- Use `conftest.py` for shared fixtures (db session, test client, auth headers)
- Test data: use factory functions, not hardcoded dicts
- Naming: `test_[feature]_[scenario]_[expected_result]`
  e.g. `test_create_user_with_duplicate_email_returns_409`

```python
# Pattern
async def test_create_user_success(client: AsyncClient):
    response = await client.post("/api/v1/users", json={"email": "a@b.com", "name": "Test"})
    assert response.status_code == 201
    data = response.json()
    assert data["email"] == "a@b.com"
```

## Frontend (vitest + testing-library)
- Location: co-located with component (`Button.test.tsx` next to `Button.tsx`)
- Use `@testing-library/react` for component tests
- Use `msw` (Mock Service Worker) to mock API calls — never mock fetch directly
- Test user interactions, not internal state

```typescript
// Pattern
it("shows error when login fails", async () => {
  server.use(http.post("/api/v1/auth/login", () => HttpResponse.json({ detail: "Bad credentials" }, { status: 401 })));
  render(<LoginForm />);
  await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText("Email"), "test@test.com");
  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button", { name: "Login" }));
  expect(await screen.findByText("Bad credentials")).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

## When to Write Tests
- After implementing any API endpoint (backend)
- After implementing any form or user flow (frontend)
- When fixing a bug — write a failing test first, then fix
- Agent should run tests after completing a module and before suggesting commit

## When NOT to Write Tests
- Pure UI styling (no logic)
- Auto-generated code (api-types.ts)
- One-off scripts
